;
; Sample Keyword Search File
;
; Blank lines, and lines beginning with a ';' are ignored.
; Keywords must contain at least 3 characters to be valid.
;
; There is a limit of 5 keywords per file in UNREGISTERED COPIES
; of The Blue Wave Offline Mail Reader.  After you have registered your
; copy, you can have as many keywords in one file as you care to.

; When Keyword searching, the reader ignores all cr's, lf's, and soft
; cr's in the message text.  Therefore it can find strings that span
; across multiple lines in the message text, like the following that
; will almost definitely find something in the FidoNet BLUEWAVE Echo!

[]Blue Wave
[]BWave

; Or, to catch all of the above, simply use:

[]Wave

; Several options are available for controlling -how- the reader searches
; for keywords.  Keyword search flags can be defined for each keyword in
; this file.  To specify a set of flags for a keyword, you must enclose the
; search flags in square brackets like these:  []

; Search Flags      What they do
; ================  ===========================================================
;   (none given)    When no search flags are given for any particular keyword,
;                   the default search behavior is assumed:  CASE INSENSITIVE
;                   compare, and the keyword will be searched in all of these
;                   fields:  To:, From:, Subject:, and the message text.
;
;        [!]        Searches for this keyword ONLY in the text (or body) of the
;                   message.  This flag has the absolute highest priority, and
;                   will override all other flags except the "Match Case"
;                   modifier and the "Whole Word" modifier.  (These 2 modifiers
;                   can be combined with *any* search flag.)
;
;        [@]        Searches for this keyword ONLY in the message header.  The
;                   message header includes the To:, From:, and Subject: fields.
;                   This flag has the second highest priority.  It will
;                   override all flags except for the '!' flag (described
;                   above).  If both '!' and '@' are specified for a keyword,
;                   the '!' will take priority and no message headers will be
;                   searched.
;
;        [T]        Searches for this keyword ONLY in the To: field of a
;                   message.  No other fields will be searched if this is the
;                   only flag given.  This flag can be combined with any of the
;                   flags that are described below ([F], [S], [X]).
;
;        [F]        Searches for this keyword ONLY in the From: field of a
;                   message.  No other fields will be searched if this is the
;                   only flag given.  This flag can be combined with any of the
;                   following flags:  [T], [S], and [X].
;
;        [S]        Searches for this keyword ONLY in the Subject: field of a
;                   message.  No other fields will be searched if this is the
;                   only flag given.  This flag can be combined with any of the
;                   following flags:  [T], [F], and [X].
;
;        [X]        Searches for this keyword ONLY in the text (body) of a
;                   message.  No other fields will be searched if this is the
;                   only flag given.  This flag can be combined with any of the
;                   following flags:  [T], [F], and [S].
;
;
; Search Modifiers  What they do
; ================  ===========================================================
;        [#]        This search modifier can be used with *any* of the above-
;                   described search flags.  This causes the keyword to only
;                   be found if it is a 'whole word'.  For example, suppose
;                   you have defined a keyword of 'and'.  If the '#' search
;                   modifier is NOT specified, the mail reader will locate
;                   the following words as 'hits':  sand, bland, Anderson.
;                   When this flag IS specified, only the word 'and' by itself
;                   will be found.
;
;        [*]        This search modifier can be used with *any* of the above-
;                   described search flags.  This causes the keyword to only
;                   be found if its UPPER/lower case matches exactly to the
;                   one given here.  For example, a keyword of "[*]DOS" will
;                   find the word "DOS", but not "Dos", "dOS", or "dossier".

;
; Remember...  The default mode of the reader is to find all matches to a
; keyword within both message headers (From:, To:, and Subj: fields), and
; within the message text.  You can control this behavior by prefixing your
; keyword with the following 'tokens':
;

; This keyword will be found in the From:, To:, and Subject: fields of a
; message, and only if it is capitalized exactly as typed here.

[@*]John Doe


; This keyword will be found in the From: and To: fields ONLY.  Upper/lower
; case does not matter, since the [*] modifier is not present.

[TF]Mary Poppins

; This keyword will be found in a message if it is located in the message text
; or the message subject.

[XS]9600 baud modem

; You can even FURTHER control the way the reader searches for keywords by
; using the [#]keyword token.  As described above, the reader will find
; matches to a keyword even *within* other words.  Let's suppose you are
; a genealogist, and you are searching an area containing 500 messages that
; may contain information about one of your relatives named "Brown".  In
; the default mode, the reader will stop you at every message that
; contained "BROWN" somewhere in the message;  Even at unwanted messages
; that might contain "Browning", "Brownman", or "Brownstone".  To search
; for only the word "Brown", and NO word that is a superset of "Brown", you
; could search for:

[#]Brown


; The flags and modifiers described above can also be combined, allowing you
; to search for WHOLE WORDS only in either the message text or the message
; header.
;
; The following keyword entry will find only the whole word SMITH in the
; message headers:

[#@]Smith

; The following keyword entry will find only the whole word SMITH in the
; message bodies (text):

[#!]Smith

; The following keyword entry will find only whole words in ALL UPPERCASE
; LETTERS, in the To:, From:, and Subject: fields, and text of the message:

[#*TFSX]MYUPPERCASEKEYWORD

; End of KEYWORDS.BW
